South Africa’s EOH said it has hired a legal firm to carry out an internal investigation as the technology company seeks to improve governance under new Chief Executive Officer Stephen van Coller. This comes as EOH faces losing two partner agreements with Microsoft Corp.’s South African unit within the next 30 days. EOH will meet with Microsoft Tuesday evening to discuss the matter, Van Coller said in a phone interview on Tuesday. Read: EOH shares plunge 29% after Microsoft termination EOH plunged 30% to R18.59 as of 10:34 am in Johannesburg, the most since December 2017.